                  </div>
                  <div class="result-row">
                    <span class="result-level">Normal</span>
                    <span class="result-meaning">Indicates a typical ovarian reserve for your age</span>
                  </div>
                  <div class="result-row">
                    <span class="result-level">Low</span>
                    <span class="result-meaning">Suggests a lower ovarian reserve; may impact fertility planning</span>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 italic mt-4">
                  Note: AMH results should be interpreted in context with other fertility tests and medical history.
                </p>
              </div>

              <!-- FAQ -->
              <div class="content-section">
                <h2 class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
                <div class="faq-container">
                  <details class="faq-item">
                    <summary class="faq-question">Do I need to fast for the AMH test?</summary>
                    <p class="faq-answer">No, fasting is not required for the AMH test.</p>
                  </details>
                  
                  <details class="faq-item">
                    <summary class="faq-question">When should I take the AMH test during my cycle?</summary>
                    <p class="faq-answer">AMH levels are stable throughout your cycle, so the test can be done on any day.</p>
                  </details>
                  
                  <details class="faq-item">
                    <summary class="faq-question">What does low AMH mean for fertility?</summary>
                    <p class="faq-answer">Low AMH suggests fewer remaining eggs but doesn't mean you can't conceive. Discuss results with your provider.</p>
                  </details>
                  
                  <details class="faq-item">
                    <summary class="faq-question">Is AMH a definitive fertility test?</summary>
                    <p class="faq-answer">No, AMH is one indicator of ovarian reserve. A complete fertility assessment includes multiple tests.</p>
                  </details>
                </div>
              </div>

              <!-- Compliance & Trust -->
              <div class="cta-section">
                <p class="cta-text">
                  <strong>CLIA-Certified & HIPAA-Compliant.</strong> This test is processed by Quest Diagnostics, 
